>>21672166 >>21672229 >>21672460
A couple thoughts on that since I've had this conversation before. Consider sci fi writers, especially in the 1960s and before all the way back to Jules Verne, would usually be more of an intellectual & sedentary class in society. Usually highly educated & living in urban environments, to imagine in general terms for common denominators. One ideal pet for many would be cats. Nice, quiet, take few resources, take care of themselves mostly, they leave typical writers-types from that time frame more quiet time to themselves. Also, cats are more engaging in a personal relationship. Not trying to shit-talk dogs, but cats stay with a person because they want to, dogs stay with a person out of loyalty & imprinting from a young age. Specific examples here can be debated, but in a big-picture generality, it would have been far more typical for writer personalities to relate to and interact with more typical cat personality than typical dog.

It was also accepted "fact" for centuries that cats are much more intelligent. While more debatable today, prior to about 1980 it was not really questioned. So a speculative fiction writer would naturally turn to an animal they had experience with, easy access to, and an "accepted" high intelligence when attempting to imagine an alien creature. Today we're much more saturated with movies & stories about alien thinking, but prior to WWII humans had little to go on when trying to imagine aliens. Cats do nicely, especially since dogs generally don't seem as alien to most people.

For what it's worth, I think cats provided one of the few models into alien intelligence that people could easily relate to prior to more elaborate science fiction that began in the 1950s & matured mostly with Star Wars in 1977.

Anonymous Mon 04 Mar 2019 13:26:03 No.21674305 Report
Quoted By:
>>21672460
I think it's because it's easy to imagine behavior based on a cat-like appearance. A lot of early science fiction aliens are, essentially, "outsiders". They're not really distinguished from humanity by a set of biological differences which inform the difference, and thus the story. They are defined by being non-human. For instance, there are many aliens that are essentially human, and more defined by having better technology or different ideology, than by their biology.

The idea of using aliens as a plot device on their own, by highlighting biological differences, seems to be a fairly recent thing in science fiction. It's also a flavor thing, as people have grown more towards a concept of "realism" in science fiction. Something that, if you ask me, seems to have grown from the increasing use of aliens as monsters in science fiction. Science fiction used to be a highly optimistic genre, after all, so there was a high amount of material that painted aliens in a favorable light, which also meant making them a lot like us. So you want aliens. So also want aliens that are easy to understand. And you want aliens that are sympathetic. You make them cats.

Added to that, animal anthropomorphism comes pretty natural to people. The very first example of animal anthropomorphism is a cat man. And if it's good enough for a guy sitting in his Stone Age cave, why shouldn't it be for a modern science fiction writer?
